Duck Typing is a type-checking technique where the type of an object is determined by the methods or properties that it has, rather than by its class. It is based on the assumption that if an object has a method or property that matches a given type, then it must be of that type. This is in contrast to TypeScript, which is a type-checking language that is based on classes and interfaces.

