```TypeScript
interface User {
  username: string;
  age: number;
  email: string;
  isAdmin: boolean;
}
```

In the example above, the User object has an age property, a username property, and an isAdmin property, all of which have a specific type. If you pass a User object to a method that requires a user object to have a username property, then the method will not be able to process the object unless the object has a username property. This ensures that the code is type-safe, which means that it will not be possible to make a mistake that causes a runtime error.

